# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cold-chain-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] A **cold chain** is a supply chain that uses refrigeration to maintain perishable goods, such as pharmaceuticals, produce or other goods that are temperature-sensitive.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Common goods, sometimes called **cool cargo,** distributed in cold chains include fresh agricultural produce, seafood, frozen food, photographic film, chemicals, and pharmaceutical products.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The objective of a cold chain is to preserve the integrity and quality of goods such as pharmaceutical products or perishable goods from production to consumption.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Unlike other goods or merchandise, cold chain goods are perishable and always en-route towards end use or destination.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Adequate cold storage, in particular, can be crucial to prevent food loss and waste.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Mobile refrigeration with ice from the ice trade began with reefer ships and refrigerator cars (iceboxes on wheels) in the mid-19th century.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The term *cold chain* was first used in 1908.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The first effective cold store in the UK opened in 1882 at St Katharine Docks.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] It could hold 59,000 carcasses, and by 1911 cold storage capacity in London had reached 2.84 million carcasses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] By 1930 about a thousand refrigerated meat containers were in use which could be switched from road to railway.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Mobile mechanical refrigeration was invented by Frederick McKinley Jones, who co-founded Thermo King with entrepreneur Joseph A.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] In 1938 Numero sold his Cinema Supplies Inc. movie sound equipment business to RCA to form the new entity, U.S.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Thermo Control Company (later the Thermo King Corporation), in partnership with Jones, his engineer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This technology has been frequently in use since the 1950s, when it was most often used for preserving animal-based cells or tissue.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] As medical breakthroughs, such as in cancer treatment, have taken place, the demand for cold chain systems has grown.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The COVID-19 pandemic and its associated vaccinations, have caused vastly increased need.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Cold chains are common in the food and pharmaceutical industries and also in some chemical shipments.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] One common temperature range for a cold chain in pharmaceutical industries is 2 to 8 °C (36 to 46 °F), but the specific temperature (and time at temperature) tolerances depend on the actual product being shipped.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Unique to fresh produce cargoes, the cold chain requires to additionally maintain product specific environment parameters which include air quality levels (carbon dioxide, oxygen, humidity and others).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The cold chain is used in the supply of vaccines to distant clinics in hot climates served by poorly developed transport networks.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Disruption of a cold chain due to war or logistical challenges may produce severe consequences, as distributed vaccines can become inert due to a lack of temperature control during transport.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The integrity of the vaccine cold chain is therefore a critical public health concern.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] For vaccines, there are different types of cold chains.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] There is an ultralow, or deep freeze, cold chain for vaccines that require -70 degrees C, such as the Ebola and Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines, and some animal vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Next the frozen chain requires -20 degrees C.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Varicella and zoster vaccinations require this level.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Then the refrigerated chain, which requires temperatures between two and eight degrees C.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Most flu vaccinations only require refrigeration.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] In 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, vaccines being developed may need ultracold storage and transportation temperatures as cold as −70 °C (−94 °F), requiring what has been referred to as a "colder chain" infrastructure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This creates some issues of distribution for the Pfizer vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] It is estimated that only 25 to 30 countries in the world have the infrastructure for the required ultracold cold chain.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The integrity of a modern cold chain is maintained by a suite of interconnected technologies that provide real-time monitoring, data logging, and operational control.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] These systems are a key part of Fleet digitalization and are essential for ensuring product safety, regulatory compliance, and operational efficiency.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The development of advanced frameworks for temperature monitoring, leveraging IoT platforms, has become a key area of innovation in logistics.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Refrigerated trucks, railcars, and reefer containers are typically equipped with advanced fleet telematics systems.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] A telematic control unit installed in the vehicle or container serves as the central hub for data collection.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Unlike standard systems, these units often interface directly with the refrigeration unit's microprocessor, allowing for two-way communication.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This enables dispatchers and fleet managers to not only receive data but also remotely adjust settings, such as the temperature setpoint.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] The specialized telemetry data transmitted in real-time is crucial for cold chain oversight.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Continuous data logging is fundamental for validation and compliance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This is achieved using standalone Temperature data loggers, RFID tags that record temperature, or, most commonly, through the integrated telematics system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This creates an unbroken digital record of a shipment's temperature history from origin to destination, which is the core of a modern **Track and trace** system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This verifiable audit trail is essential for meeting regulatory standards like HACCP and Good Distribution Practice (GDP), and for accurately determining the remaining shelf life of a product.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Modern route planning software can optimize routes not only for time and fuel efficiency but also to minimize risks to temperature-sensitive cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This can include avoiding areas with high ambient temperatures or known traffic congestion that could strain refrigeration units.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Furthermore, Driver scoring systems are used to monitor driving behavior.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] Gentle driving with smooth acceleration and braking is important to prevent load shifting and damage to delicate products like fresh produce or pharmaceuticals.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] For high-value cargo, **video telematics** systems with interior and exterior-facing cameras provide an additional layer of oversight.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] This technology can be used to verify that proper loading and unloading protocols are followed to minimize the time cargo doors are open.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/cold-chain] It also enhances security, which, when combined with GPS tracking, is a critical component for the Stolen vehicle recovery of valuable shipments such as pharmaceuticals.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Animals, such as earthworms, also help decompose the organic materials on and in soil through their activities.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Organisms that do this are known as decomposers or detritivores.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The science which studies decomposition is generally referred to as *taphonomy* from the Greek word *taphos*, meaning 'tomb'.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition will begin at the moment of death, caused by two factors: autolysis, the breaking down of tissues by the body's own internal chemicals and enzymes, and putrefaction, the breakdown of tissues by bacteria.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] These processes release compounds such as cadaverine and putrescine, that are the chief source of the unmistakably putrid odor of decaying animal tissue.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Prime decomposers are bacteria or fungi, though larger scavengers also play an important role in decomposition if the body is accessible to insects, mites and other animals.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Additionally, soil animals are considered key regulators of decomposition at local scales but their role at larger scales is unresolved.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The most important arthropods that are involved in the process include carrion beetles, mites, the flesh flies (Sarcophagidae) and blowflies (Calliphoridae), such as the green bottle flies seen in the summer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In North America, the most important non-insect animals that are typically involved in the process include mammal and bird scavengers, such as coyotes, dogs, wolves, foxes, rats, crows and vultures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Some of these scavengers also remove and scatter bones, which they ingest at a later time.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Aquatic and marine environments have break-down agents that include bacteria, fish, crustaceans, fly larvae and other carrion scavengers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Five general stages are typically used to describe the process of decomposition in vertebrate animals: fresh, bloat, active decay, advanced decay, and dry/remains.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The general stages of decomposition are coupled with two stages of chemical decomposition: autolysis and putrefaction.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] These two stages contribute to the chemical process of decomposition, which breaks down the main components of the body.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] With death the microbiome of the living organism collapses and is followed by the necrobiome that undergoes predictable changes over time.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Among those animals that have a heart, the *fresh* stage begins immediately after the heart stops beating.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] From the moment of death, the body begins cooling or warming to match the temperature of the ambient environment, during a stage called algor mortis.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Shortly after death, within three to six hours, the muscular tissues become rigid and incapable of relaxing, during a stage called rigor mortis.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Since blood is no longer being pumped through the body, gravity causes it to drain to the dependent portions of the body, creating an overall bluish-purple discoloration termed livor mortis or, more commonly, lividity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Depending on the position of the body, these parts would vary.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] For instance, if the person was flat on their back when they died, the blood would collect in the parts that are touching the ground.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] If the person was hanging, it would collect in their fingertips, toes and earlobes.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Once the heart stops, the blood can no longer supply oxygen or remove carbon dioxide from the tissues.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The resulting decrease in pH and other chemical changes cause cells to lose their structural integrity, bringing about the release of cellular enzymes capable of initiating the breakdown of surrounding cells and tissues.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Visible changes caused by decomposition are limited during the fresh stage, although autolysis may cause blisters to appear at the surface of the skin.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The small amount of oxygen remaining in the body is quickly depleted by cellular metabolism and aerobic microbes naturally present in respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts, creating an ideal environment for the proliferation of anaerobic organisms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] These multiply, consuming the body's carbohydrates, lipids and proteins, to produce a variety of substances including propionic acid, lactic acid, methane, hydrogen sulfide and ammonia.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The process of microbial proliferation within a body is referred to as putrefaction and leads to the second stage of decomposition known as bloat.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Blowflies and flesh flies are the first carrion insects to arrive and they seek a suitable oviposition site.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The bloat stage provides the first clear visual sign that microbial proliferation is underway.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In this stage, anaerobic metabolism takes place, leading to the accumulation of gases, such as hydrogen sulfide, carbon dioxide, methane and nitrogen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The accumulation of gases within the bodily cavity causes the distention of the abdomen and gives a cadaver its overall bloated appearance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The gases produced also cause natural liquids and liquefying tissues to become frothy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] As the pressure of the gases within the body increases, fluids are forced to escape from natural orifices, such as the nose, mouth and anus, and enter the surrounding environment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The buildup of pressure combined with the loss of integrity of the skin may also cause the body to rupture.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Intestinal anaerobic bacteria transform haemoglobin into sulfhemoglobin and other colored pigments.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The associated gases which accumulate within the body at this time aid in the transport of sulfhemoglobin throughout the body via the circulatory and lymphatic systems, giving the body an overall marbled appearance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] If insects have access, maggots hatch and begin to feed on the body's tissues.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Maggot activity, typically confined to natural orifices, and masses under the skin, causes the skin to slip, and hair to detach from the skin.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Maggot feeding, and the accumulation of gases within the body, eventually leads to post-mortem skin ruptures which will then further allow purging of gases and fluids into the surrounding environment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Ruptures in the skin allow oxygen to re-enter the body and provide more surface area for the development of fly larvae and the activity of aerobic microorganisms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The purging of gases and fluids results in the strong distinctive odors associated with decay.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Active decay is characterized by the period of greatest mass loss.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This loss occurs as a result of both the voracious feeding of maggots and the purging of decomposition fluids into the surrounding environment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The purged fluids accumulate around the body and create a cadaver decomposition island (CDI).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Liquefaction of tissues and disintegration become apparent during this time and strong odors persist.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The end of active decay is signaled by the migration of maggots away from the body to pupate.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition is largely inhibited during advanced decay due to the loss of readily available cadaveric material.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Insect activity is also reduced during this stage.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] When the carcass is located on soil, the area surrounding it will show evidence of vegetation death.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The CDI surrounding the carcass will display an increase in soil carbon and nutrients such as phosphorus, potassium, calcium and magnesium; changes in pH; and a significant increase in soil nitrogen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] As the ecosystem recovers from the disturbance, the CDI moves into the dry/remains stage, which is characterized by a decrease in the intensity of the disturbance and an increase in the amount of plant growth around the affected area.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This is a sign that the nutrients and other ecological resources present in the surrounding soil have not yet returned to their normal levels.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] During this stage, it is important to monitor the ecosystem for any signs of continued disturbance or ecological stress.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The resurgence of plant growth is a positive sign, but it may take several years for the ecosystem to fully recover and return to its pre-disturbance state.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] All that remains of the cadaver at this stage is dry skin, cartilage, and bones, which will become dry and bleached if exposed to the elements.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] If all soft tissue is removed from the cadaver, it is referred to as completely skeletonized, but if only portions of the bones are exposed, it is referred to as partially skeletonized.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] A dead body that has been exposed to the open elements, such as water and air, will decompose more quickly and attract much more insect activity than a body that is buried or confined in special protective gear or artifacts.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This is due, in part, to the limited number of insects that can penetrate soil and the lower temperatures under the soil.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The rate and manner of decomposition in an animal body are strongly affected by several factors.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The speed at which decomposition occurs varies greatly.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Factors such as temperature, humidity, and the season of death all determine how fast a fresh body will skeletonize or mummify.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] A basic guide for the effect of environment on decomposition is given as Casper's Law (or Ratio): if all other factors are equal, then, when there is free access of air a body decomposes twice as fast as if immersed in water and eight times faster than if buried in the earth.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Ultimately, the rate of bacterial decomposition acting on the tissue will depend upon the temperature of the surroundings.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Colder temperatures decrease the rate of decomposition while warmer temperatures increase it.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] A dry body will not decompose efficiently.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Moisture helps the growth of microorganisms that decompose the organic matter, but too much moisture could lead to anaerobic conditions slowing down the decomposition process.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The most important variable is the body's accessibility to insects, particularly flies.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] On the surface in tropical areas, invertebrates alone can easily reduce a fully fleshed corpse to clean bones in under two weeks.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The skeleton itself is not permanent; acids in soils can reduce it to unrecognizable components.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This is one reason given for the lack of human remains found in the wreckage of the *Titanic*, even in parts of the ship considered inaccessible to scavengers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Freshly skeletonized bone is often called *green* bone and has a characteristic greasy feel.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Under certain conditions (underwater, but also cool, damp soil), bodies may undergo saponification and develop a waxy substance called adipocere, caused by the action of soil chemicals on the body's proteins and fats.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The formation of adipocere slows decomposition by inhibiting the bacteria that cause putrefaction.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In extremely dry or cold conditions, the normal process of decomposition is halted—by either lack of moisture or temperature controls on bacterial and enzymatic action—causing the body to be preserved as a mummy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Frozen mummies commonly restart the decomposition process when thawed (see Ötzi the Iceman), whilst heat-desiccated mummies remain so unless exposed to moisture.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The bodies of newborns who never ingested food are an important exception to the normal process of decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] They lack the internal microbial flora that produces much of decomposition and quite commonly mummify if kept in even moderately dry conditions.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Aerobic decomposition takes place in the presence of oxygen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Living organisms that use oxygen to survive feed on the body.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Anaerobic decomposition takes place in the absence of oxygen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This could be a place where the body is buried in organic material and oxygen cannot reach it.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This process of putrefaction has a bad odor accompanied by it due to the hydrogen sulfide and organic matter containing sulfur.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Embalming is the practice of delaying the decomposition of human and animal remains.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Embalming slows decomposition somewhat but does not forestall it indefinitely.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Embalmers typically pay great attention to parts of the body seen by mourners, such as the face and hands.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The chemicals used in embalming repel most insects and slow down bacterial putrefaction by either killing existing bacteria in or on the body themselves or by fixing cellular proteins, which means that they cannot act as a nutrient source for subsequent bacterial infections.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In sufficiently dry environments, an embalmed body may end up mummified and it is not uncommon for bodies to remain preserved to a viewable extent after decades.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] A body buried in a sufficiently dry environment may be well preserved for decades.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This was observed in the case for murdered civil rights activist Medgar Evers, who was found to be almost perfectly preserved over 30 years after his death, permitting an accurate autopsy when the case of his murder was re-opened in the 1990s.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Bodies submerged in a peat bog may become naturally embalmed, arresting decomposition and resulting in a preserved specimen known as a bog body.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The generally cool and anoxic conditions in these environments limits the rate of microbial activity, thus limiting the potential for decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The time for an embalmed body to be reduced to a skeleton varies greatly.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Even when a body is decomposed, embalming treatment can still be achieved (the arterial system decays more slowly) but would not restore a natural appearance without extensive reconstruction and cosmetic work, and is largely used to control the foul odors due to decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] An animal can be preserved almost perfectly, for millions of years in a resin such as amber.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] There are some examples where bodies have been inexplicably preserved (with no human intervention) for decades or centuries and appear almost the same as when they died.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In some religious groups, this is known as incorruptibility.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] It is not known whether or for how long a body can stay free of decay without artificial preservation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The University of Tennessee Anthropological Research Facility (better known as the Body Farm) in Knoxville, Tennessee, has several bodies laid out in various situations in a fenced-in plot near the medical center.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Scientists at the Body Farm study how the human body decays in various circumstances to gain a better understanding of decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition of plant matter occurs in many stages.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] It begins with leaching by water; the most easily lost and soluble carbon compounds are liberated in this process.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Another early process is physical breakup or fragmentation of the plant material into smaller pieces, providing greater surface area for colonization and attack by decomposers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Following this, the plant detritus (consisting of cellulose, hemicellulose, microbial metabolites, and lignin) undergoes chemical alteration by microbes.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Different types of compounds decompose at different rates.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This is dependent on their chemical structure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] For instance, lignin is a component of wood, which is relatively resistant to decomposition and can in fact only be decomposed by certain fungi, such as the white-rot fungi.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Wood decomposition is a complex process involving fungi which transport nutrients to the nutritionally scarce wood from outside environment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Because of this nutritional enrichment, the fauna of saproxylic insects may develop and, in turn, affect dead wood, contributing to decomposition and nutrient cycling in the forest floor.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Lignin is one such remaining product of decomposing plants with a very complex chemical structure, causing the rate of microbial breakdown to slow.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Warmth increases the speed of plant decay by roughly the same amount, regardless of the composition of the plant.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The chemical aspects of plant decomposition always involve the release of carbon dioxide.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In fact, decomposition contributes over 90 percent of carbon dioxide released each year.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The decomposition of food, either plant or animal, called *spoilage* in this context, is an important field of study within food science.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Food decomposition can be slowed down by conservation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The spoilage of meat occurs, if the meat is untreated, in a matter of hours or days and results in the meat becoming unappetizing, poisonous or infectious.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Spoilage is caused by the practically unavoidable infection and subsequent decomposition of meat by bacteria and fungi, which are borne by the animal itself, by the people handling the meat, and by their implements.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Meat can be kept edible for a much longer time—though not indefinitely—if proper hygiene is observed during production and processing, and if appropriate food safety, food preservation and food storage procedures are applied.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Spoilage of food is attributed to contamination from microorganisms such as bacteria, molds and yeasts, along with natural decay of the food.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] These decomposition bacteria reproduce at rapid rates under conditions of moisture and preferred temperatures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] When the proper conditions are lacking the bacteria may form spores which lurk until suitable conditions arise to continue reproduction.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition rates and speed may differ or vary due to abiotic factors such as moisture level, temperature, and soil type.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] They also vary depending on the initial amount of breakdown caused by the prior consumers in the food chain.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] This means the form that organic matter is in, original plant or animal, partially eaten, or as faecal matter when the detritivore encounters it.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The more broken down the matter, the faster the final decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The rate of decomposition is governed by three sets of factors: the physical environment (temperature, moisture and soil properties), the quantity and quality of the dead material available to decomposers, and the nature of the microbial community itself.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition rates are low under very wet or very dry conditions.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition rates are highest in damp, moist conditions with adequate levels of oxygen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Wet soils tend to become deficient in oxygen (this is especially true in wetlands), which slows microbial growth.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] In dry soils, decomposition slows as well, but bacteria continue to grow (albeit at a slower rate) even after soils become too dry to support plant growth.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] When the rains return and soils become wet, the osmotic gradient between the bacterial cells and the soil water causes the cells to gain water quickly.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Under these conditions, many bacterial cells burst, releasing a pulse of nutrients.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Decomposition rates also tend to be slower in acidic soils.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Soils which are rich in clay minerals tend to have lower decomposition rates, and thus, higher levels of organic matter.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The smaller particles of clay result in a larger surface area that can hold water.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The higher the water content of a soil, the lower the oxygen content and, consequently, the lower the rate of decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Clay minerals also bind particles of organic material to their surface, making them less accessible to microbes.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Soil disturbance like tilling increases decomposition by increasing the amount of oxygen in the soil and by exposing new organic matter to soil microbes.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The quality and quantity of the material available to decomposers is another major factor that influences the rate of decomposition.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Substances like sugars and amino acids decompose readily and are considered labile.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Cellulose and hemicellulose, which are broken down more slowly, are "moderately labile".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Compounds which are more resistant to decay, like lignin or cutin, are considered recalcitrant.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Litter with a higher proportion of labile compounds decomposes much more rapidly than does litter with a higher proportion of recalcitrant material.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Consequently, dead animals decompose more rapidly than dead leaves, which themselves decompose more rapidly than fallen branches.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] As organic material in the soil ages, its quality decreases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] The more labile compounds decompose quickly, leaving an increasing proportion of recalcitrant material called humus.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/perishable] Microbial cell walls also contain recalcitrant materials like chitin, and these also accumulate as the microbes die, further reducing the quality of older soil organic matter.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] A **refrigerated cargo ship**, also known as a **reefer ship**, is a refrigerated cargo ship typically used to transport perishable cargo, which require temperature-controlled handling, such as fruits, meat, vegetables, dairy products, and similar items.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] **Conventional vessels** have a traditional cargo operation with top opening hatches and cranes/derricks.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] On such ships, when facing wet weather, the hatches need to be closed to prevent heavy rain from flooding the holds.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Both above ship types are well suited for the handling of palletized and loose cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] **Refrigerated container ships** are specifically designed to carry containerised unit loads where each container has its individual refrigerated unit.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] These containers are nearly always twenty-foot equivalent units (often called TEU) that are the size of "standard" cargo containers that are loaded and unloaded at container terminals and aboard container ships.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] These ships differ from conventional container ships in their design, power generation, and electrical distribution equipment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They need provisions made for powering each container's cooling system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Because of their ease of loading and unloading cargo many container ships are now being built or redesigned to carry refrigerated containers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] A major use of refrigerated cargo hold type ships was for the transportation of bananas and frozen meat, but most of these ships have been partly replaced by refrigerated containers that have a refrigeration system attached to the rear end of the container.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] While on a ship these containers are plugged into an electrical outlet (typically 440 VAC) that ties into the ship's power generation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Refrigerated container ships are not limited by the number of refrigeration containers they can carry, unlike other container ships which may be limited in their number of refrigeration outlets or have insufficient generator capacity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Each reefer container unit is typically designed with a stand-alone electrical circuit and has its own breaker switch that allows it to be connected and disconnected as required.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In principle each individual unit could be repaired while the ship was still underway.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Refrigerated cargo is a key part of the income for some shipping companies.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] On multi-purpose ships, refrigerated containers are mostly carried above deck, as they have to be checked for proper operation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Also, a major part of the refrigeration system (such as a compressor) may fail, which would have to be replaced or unplugged quickly in the event of a fire.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Modern container vessels stow the reefer containers in cellguides with adjacent inspection walkways that enable reefer containers to be carried in the holds as well as on the deck.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Modern refrigerated container vessels are designed to incorporate a water-cooling system for containers stowed under deck.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] This does not replace the refrigeration system but facilitates cooling down of the external machinery.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Containers stowed on the exposed upper deck are air-cooled, while those under deck are water-cooled.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The water cooling design allows additional refrigerated containers under deck, as water can be used to dissipate the high amount of heat they generate.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] This system draws fresh water from the ship's water supply, which in turn transfers the heat through heat exchangers to the abundantly available sea water.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] There are also refrigeration systems that have two compressors for very precise and low-temperature operations, such as transporting a container of blood to a war zone.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Cargoes of shrimp, asparagus, caviar and blood are considered among the most expensive refrigerated items.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Bananas, fruit and meat have historically been the main cargo of refrigerated ships.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In 1869, reefers were shipping beef carcasses frozen in a salt-ice mixture from Indianola, Texas, to New Orleans, Louisiana, to be served in hospitals, hotels, and restaurants.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In 1874, shipping of frozen beef from America to London had already begun, which developed into an annual tonnage of around 10,000 short tons (8,900 long tons; 9,100 t).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The insulated cargo space was cooled by ice, which was loaded on departure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The success of this method was limited by insulation, loading techniques, ice block size, distance and climate.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The first attempt to ship refrigerated meat across the Pacific was made when the *Northam* sailed from Australia to the UK in 1876.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The refrigeration machinery broke down en route and the cargo was lost.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In the same 1876, French inventor Charles Tellier bought the ex-Elder-Dempster a 690 tons cargo ship *Eboe* and fitted a Methyl-ether refrigerating plant of his design.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The ship was renamed *Le Frigorifique* and successfully imported a cargo of refrigerated meat from Argentina.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] However the machinery could be improved and in 1877 another refrigerated ship called *Paraguay* with a refrigerating plant improved by Ferdinand Carré was put into service on the South American run.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] *Paraguay* completed the first successful travel with its shipment of 5500 frozen muttons from Argentina arriving to France in excellent condition despite a collision that delayed the delivery for several months, thus proving the concept of refrigerated ships, if not the economics.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In 1879, *Strathleven*, equipped with compression refrigeration, sailed successfully from Sydney to the UK with 40 tons of frozen beef and mutton as a small part of her cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The clipper sailing ship *Dunedin*, owned by the New Zealand and Australian Land Company (NZALC), was refitted in 1881 with a Bell-Coleman compression refrigeration machine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] This freezer unit worked by compressing air, then releasing it into the hold of the ship.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The expanding air absorbed heat as it expanded, cooling the cargo in the hold.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] *Dunedin*'s most visible sign of being an unusual ship was the funnel for the refrigeration plant placed between her fore and main masts (sometimes leading her to be mistaken for a steamship which had been common since the 1840s).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In February 1882, *Dunedin* sailed from Port Chalmers, New Zealand, with 4,331 mutton, 598 lamb and 22 pig carcasses, 246 kegs of butter, and hare, pheasant, turkey, chicken and 2,226 sheep tongues.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] It arrived in London after sailing 98 days with its cargo still frozen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] After meeting all costs, the NZALC company made a £4,700 profit from the voyage.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Soon after *Dunedin*'s successful voyage, an extensive frozen meat trade from New Zealand and Australia to the UK was developed with over 16 different refrigerated and passenger refrigerated ships built or refitted by 1900 in Scotland and Northern England shipyards for this trade.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Within 5 years, 172 shipments of frozen meat were sent from New Zealand to the United Kingdom.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Refrigerated shipping also led to a broader meat and dairy boom in Australia, New Zealand and Argentina.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Frozen meat and dairy exports continue to form the backbone of New Zealand's economy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The Nelson brothers, butchers in County Meath, Ireland, started shipping extensive live beef shipments to Liverpool, England.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They successfully expanded their beef business until their imports from Ireland were insufficient to supply their rapidly growing business and Nelson decided to investigate the possibility of importing meat from Argentina.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The first refrigerated ship they bought was *Spindrift* which they renamed in 1890 SS *Highland Scot*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] A vessel of 3,060 gross tons bought by James Nelson and Sons in 1889 and fitted with a somewhat primitive refrigerating plant operating on the cold air system became one of the pioneer vessels in the trade of refrigerated meat and other perishable commodities.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They hauled beef carcasses from Argentina to Britain.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Their regularly scheduled shipments and ships developed into the Nelson Line that was formed in 1880 for the meat trade from Argentina to UK.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Refrigeration made it possible to import meat from the United States, New Zealand, Argentina and Australia.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The United Fruit Company has used some type of reefers, often combined with cruise ship passenger accommodations, since about 1889.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Because of their cargo was mostly bananas, they were nicknamed the "Banana Fleet".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Since bananas are relatively light and the normal shipping route was to Central America and then back to various US ports, these ships were often built as combination cargo ships and what are now called cruise ships to pay for more of their operating expenses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] After about 1910, they called these combination cruise and cargo ships the "Great White Fleet" based on their heat-reducing white paint.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] To avoid US shipping regulations and taxes they are registered in about six other countries, with very few now maintaining US registry.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] European associates with their own ships were often employed to ship fruit to Europe.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] United Brands was taken over by Chiquita Brands International in the 1980s and owns the largest fleet of banana boats in the world, but none of them now sails under the US flag.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] SS *Pastores* and SS *Calamares* were built in Ireland in 1912 and 1913 for the United Fruit Company as a combination cruise ship and refrigerated cargo ship.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The United Fruit Company's fleet of about 85 ships was one of the largest civilian fleets in the world.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] These ships normally carried up to 95 cruise ship passengers and a crew to ports in Central America and then would return to the United States with passengers and a cargo of refrigerated bananas and miscellaneous cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The renamed USS *Pastores* and USS *Calamares* were taken over by the United States Navy in World War I and used to take troops and refrigerated supplies to and from Europe.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] After hostilities ceased they were returned to United Fruit Company in 1919.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They were requisitioned again on 2 June 1941 from United Fruit for use in World War II.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] After hostilities ceased they were then returned again to United Fruit Company in 1946.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In World War I, the US Navy contracted for 18 refrigerated ships for hauling provisions to the troops in Europe.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They were launched 1918 and 1919 as the war was ending and were nearly all scrapped by 1933 in the Great Depression as an economy move.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Most were built in Baltimore Dry Dock in Baltimore, Maryland, Moore Dry Dock Company in Oakland, California, and Standard SB Co. in Shooters Island, New York.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] The *Mizar*-class stores ships were six United Fruit passenger and refrigerated cargo liners built in 1931–1933 that the United States Maritime Commission requisitioned in 1941–1942.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] They were USS *Antigua*, USS *Ariel*, USS *Merak*, USS *Mizar*, USS *Talamanca* and USS *Tarazed*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] *Antigua*, although requisitioned, was never commissioned into the Navy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] United States Maritime Commission Type R ship were Reefer ships.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In April 1943, the Navy also requisitioned SS *Ulua* from the United Fruit Co.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] After US navy officers boarded the ship and took possession as it approached the Golden Gate Bridge, the ship became the USS *Octans*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] It was the last of the UFC 'reefer' ships to be taken over.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Other reefers converted for US Navy use were the Danish ships USS *Pontiac*, USS *Roamer* and USS *Uranus*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] In addition, the US Maritime Commission ordered 41 new refrigerated ships for the Navy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Because of the difficulty of building refrigerated ships only two were delivered in 1944.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] According to the CIA's *The World Factbook*, there were about 38,000 registered merchant ships in the world in 2010, of which about 920 were designed as refrigerated cargo ships.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] Because of the proliferation of self-contained refrigerated container systems on container ships, there are many more ships than those designed for only refrigerated cargo that are also carrying some refrigerated cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/reefer-ship] As of 2010, the countries with the largest numbers of reefer ships in their registries are the world's two most prominent flags of convenience: Panama with 212 and Liberia with 109.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] A **refrigerated container** or **reefer** is an intermodal container (shipping container) used in intermodal freight transport that is capable of refrigeration for the transportation of temperature-sensitive, perishable cargo.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] These containers are a critical component of the cold chain, the supply chain that preserves goods like fruits, vegetables, meat, and pharmaceuticals at a specific low temperature.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] While a reefer has an integral refrigeration unit, it relies on external power from electrical power points (“reefer points”) at a land-based site, a container ship, or on a quay.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] When being transported over the road on a trailer or over a rail wagon, it can be powered from a diesel-powered generator ("gen set") that attaches to the container during road journeys.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Refrigerated containers are capable of maintaining a constant internal temperature ranging from −65 °C (−85 °F) up to 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The market for cold chain tracking solutions is growing rapidly, driven by the increasing global demand for fresh food and temperature-sensitive pharmaceuticals.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The number of active tracking devices for refrigerated containers is projected to grow significantly, highlighting the increasing importance of this technology for ensuring food safety and product integrity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The impact on society of reefer containers is vast, allowing consumers all over the world to enjoy fresh produce at any time of year.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Modern refrigerated containers are often equipped with a telematic control unit and a GPS tracking unit that enables remote monitoring of the container's parameters as part of a fleet telematics system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] This integration is part of the fleet digitalization of the logistics industry, making the container an element of a larger Vehicle tracking system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The system allows a fleet management operator to track the container's location and monitor internal parameters such as temperature, humidity, and door status.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] This continuous stream of telemetry provides a complete track and trace record of the container's temperature throughout its journey, which helps ensure the integrity of the cold chain.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] If the temperature deviates from the set point, the system can send an automatic alert to the operator, allowing for immediate intervention.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] These systems also allow for remote control, enabling an operator to change the temperature settings or turn the refrigeration unit on or off from a central software platform.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Another refrigeration system sometimes used where the journey time is short is total loss refrigeration, in which frozen carbon dioxide ice (or sometimes liquid nitrogen) is used for cooling.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The cryogenically frozen gas slowly evaporates, and thus cools the container and is vented from it.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] The container is cooled for as long as there is frozen gas available in the system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] These have been used in railcars for many years, providing up to 17 days temperature regulation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Whilst refrigerated containers are not common for air transport, total loss dry ice systems are usually used.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] These containers have a chamber which is loaded with solid carbon dioxide and the temperature is regulated by a thermostatically controlled electric fan, and the air freight versions are intended to maintain temperature for up to around 100 hours.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Full-size intermodal containers equipped with these "cryogenic" systems can maintain their temperature for the 30 days needed for sea transport.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Since they do not require an external power supply, cryogenically refrigerated containers can be stored anywhere on any vessel that can accommodate "dry" (un-refrigerated) ocean freight containers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Valuable, temperature-sensitive, or hazardous cargo often require the utmost in system reliability.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] This type of reliability can only be achieved through the installation of a **redundant refrigeration system**.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] A redundant refrigeration system consists of integrated primary and back-up refrigeration units.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] If the primary unit malfunctions, the secondary unit automatically starts.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] To provide reliable power to the refrigeration units, these containers are often fitted with one or more diesel generator sets.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerated-container] Containers fitted with these systems may be required for transporting certain dangerous goods in order to comply with the International Maritime Organization’s regulations.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] A **refrigerator truck** or **chiller lorry** (also called a **reefer**), is a van or truck designed to carry perishable freight at low temperatures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] Most long-distance refrigerated transport by truck is done in articulated trucks pulling refrigerated hardside (box) semi-trailers, although insulated curtainsiders are common in some countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] Occasionally, refrigerated trailers have been used as temporary morgues, and second-hand refrigerated trailers are frequently sold for use in tiny home conversions due to their insulation and existing status as a vehicle.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] The first successful mechanically refrigerated trucks were made for the ice cream industry in 1925.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] American inventor Frederick McKinley Jones is known to be the first person to invent a refrigerated truck.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] There were around 4 million refrigerated road vehicles in use in 2010 worldwide.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] Like refrigerator cars, refrigerated trucks differ from simple insulated and ventilated vans (commonly used for transporting fruit), neither of which are fitted with cooling apparatus.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] Refrigerator trucks can be cooled with ice, dry ice, liquid carbon dioxide, or mechanical refrigeration systems (transport refrigeration units, TRUs) powered by small displacement engines or by the truck's main engine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] They are often equipped with small "vent doors" at the rear and front of the trailer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/refrigerator-truck] These doors are kept open while hauling non-refrigerated cargo (often "backhaul") to air out the trailer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] A **temperature data logger**, also called **temperature monitor**, is a portable measurement instrument that is capable of autonomously recording temperature over a defined period of time.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] The digital data can be retrieved, viewed and evaluated after it has been recorded.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] A data logger is commonly used to monitor shipments in a cold chain and to gather temperature data from diverse field conditions.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] A variety of constructions are available.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Most have an internal thermistor or thermocouple or can be connected to external sources.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Sampling and measurement are periodically taken and digitally stored.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Some have a built in display of data or out-of-tolerance warnings.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Data retrieval can be by cable, RFID, wireless systems, etc.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] They generally are small, battery powered, portable, and equipped with a microprocessor, internal memory for data storage, and sensors.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Some data loggers interface with personal computers or smart phones for set-up, control, and analysis.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Some include other sensors such as relative humidity, wind, light, tilt, shock, vibrations etc.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Others may record input from GPS devices.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Autonomous data loggers can be taken to diverse locations that cannot easily support fixed temperature monitoring equipment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] These might include: mountains, deserts, jungles, mines, ice flows, caves, etc.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Portable data loggers are also used in industry and laboratory situations where stand-alone recording is desired.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Temperature sensitive products such as foods, pharmaceuticals, and some chemicals are often monitored during shipment and logistics operations.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Exposure to temperatures outside of an acceptable range, for a critical time period, can degrade the product or shorten shelf life.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Regulations and contracts make temperature monitoring mandatory for some products.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Battery-powered, formerly mechanical, the data logger is today an electronic device that can be programmed to record individual values over periods of a few hours to several months.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Most are used to monitor temperature conditions, and some versions can also measure the relative humidity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Data loggers are often small enough to be placed inside an insulated shipping container or directly attached to a product inside a refrigerator truck or a refrigerated container.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] These monitor the temperature of the product being shipped.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Some data loggers are placed on the outside of the package or in the truck or intermodal container to monitor the air temperature.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Placement of data loggers and sensors is critical: Studies have shown that temperatures inside a truck or intermodal container are strongly affected by proximity to exterior walls and roof and to locations on the lading.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Modern digital data loggers are very portable and record the actual times and temperatures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] This information can be used to model product degradation and to pinpoint the location and cause of excessive exposure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] The measured data reveals whether the goods in transit have been subjected to potentially damaging temperature extremes or an excessive Mean kinetic temperature.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Multiple replicate shipments of data loggers are also used to compare modes of shipment (routes, vendors) and to develop composite data to be used in package testing protocols.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] There are many brands and models of data loggers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/temperature-data-logger] Most are a connectable device that must be plugged into a computer to extract the data that the logger has logged.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A **vaccine** is a biological preparation that provides active acquired immunity to a particular infectious or malignant disease.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The safety and effectiveness of vaccines has been widely studied and verified.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A vaccine typically contains an agent that resembles a disease-causing microorganism and is often made from weakened or killed forms of the microbe, its toxins, or one of its surface proteins.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The agent stimulates the immune system to recognize the agent as a threat, destroy it, and recognize further and destroy any of the microorganisms associated with that agent that it may encounter in the future.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines can be prophylactic (to prevent or alleviate the effects of a future infection by a natural or "wild" pathogen), or therapeutic (to fight a disease that has already occurred, such as cancer).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some vaccines offer full sterilizing immunity, in which infection is prevented.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The administration of vaccines is called vaccination.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccination is the most effective method of preventing infectious diseases; widespread immunity due to vaccination is largely responsible for the worldwide eradication of smallpox and the restriction of diseases such as polio, measles, and tetanus from much of the world.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) reports that licensed vaccines are available for twenty-five different preventable infections.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The first recorded use of inoculation to prevent smallpox (see variolation) occurred in the 16th century in China, with the earliest hints of the practice in China coming during the 10th century.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] It was also the first disease for which a vaccine was produced.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The folk practice of inoculation against smallpox was brought from Turkey to Britain in 1721 by Lady Mary Wortley Montagu.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The terms *vaccine* and *vaccination* are derived from *Variolae vaccinae* (smallpox of the cow), the term devised by Edward Jenner (who both developed the concept of vaccines and created the first vaccine) to denote cowpox.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] He used the phrase in 1798 for the long title of his *Inquiry into the Variolae vaccinae Known as the Cow Pox*, in which he described the protective effect of cowpox against smallpox.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In 1881, to honor Jenner, Louis Pasteur proposed that the terms should be extended to cover the new protective inoculations then being developed.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The science of vaccine development and production is termed *vaccinology*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] There is overwhelming scientific consensus that vaccines are a very safe and effective way to fight and eradicate infectious diseases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The immune system recognizes vaccine agents as foreign, destroys them, and "remembers" them.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In 1958, there were 763,094 cases of measles in the United States; 552 deaths resulted.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] After the introduction of new vaccines, the number of cases dropped to fewer than 150 per year (median of 56).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In early 2008, there were 64 suspected cases of measles.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Fifty-four of those infections were associated with importation from another country, although only thirteen percent were actually acquired outside the United States; 63 of the 64 individuals either had never been vaccinated against measles or were uncertain whether they had been vaccinated.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The measles vaccine is estimated to prevent a million deaths every year.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines led to the eradication of smallpox, one of the most contagious and deadly diseases in humans.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Other diseases such as rubella, polio, measles, mumps, chickenpox, and typhoid are nowhere near as common as they were a hundred years ago thanks to widespread vaccination programs.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] As long as the vast majority of people are vaccinated, it is much more difficult for an outbreak of disease to occur, let alone spread.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Polio, which is transmitted only among humans, is targeted by an extensive eradication campaign that has seen endemic polio restricted to only parts of three countries (Afghanistan, Nigeria, and Pakistan).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] However, the difficulty of reaching all children, cultural misunderstandings, and disinformation have caused the anticipated eradication date to be missed several times.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines also help prevent the development of antibiotic resistance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] For example, by greatly reducing the incidence of pneumonia caused by *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, vaccine programs have greatly reduced the prevalence of infections resistant to penicillin or other first-line antibiotics.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Limitations to their effectiveness, nevertheless, exist.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Sometimes, protection fails for vaccine-related reasons such as failures in vaccine attenuation, vaccination regimens or administration.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Failure may also occur for host-related reasons if the host's immune system does not respond adequately or at all.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Host-related lack of response occurs in an estimated 2–10% of individuals, due to factors including genetics, immune status, age, health and nutritional status.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] One type of primary immunodeficiency disorder resulting in genetic failure is X-linked agammaglobulinemia, in which the absence of an enzyme essential for B cell development prevents the host's immune system from generating antibodies to a pathogen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Host–pathogen interactions and responses to infection are dynamic processes involving multiple pathways in the immune system.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A host does not develop antibodies instantaneously: while the body's innate immunity may be activated in as little as twelve hours, adaptive immunity can take 1–2 weeks to fully develop.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] During that time, the host can still become infected.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Once antibodies are produced, they may promote immunity in any of several ways, depending on the class of antibodies involved.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Their success in clearing or inactivating a pathogen will depend on the amount of antibodies produced and on the extent to which those antibodies are effective at countering the strain of the pathogen involved, since different strains may be differently susceptible to a given immune reaction.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In some cases vaccines may result in partial immune protection (in which immunity is less than 100% effective but still reduces risk of infection) or in temporary immune protection (in which immunity wanes over time) rather than full or permanent immunity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] They can still raise the reinfection threshold for the population as a whole and make a substantial impact.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] They can also mitigate the severity of infection, resulting in a lower mortality rate, lower morbidity, faster recovery from illness, and a wide range of other effects.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Those who are older often display less of a response than those who are younger, a pattern known as Immunosenescence.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Adjuvants commonly are used to boost immune response, particularly for older people whose immune response to a simple vaccine may have weakened.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] If a vaccinated individual does develop the disease vaccinated against (breakthrough infection), the disease is likely to be less severe and less transmissible than in unvaccinated cases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccinations given to children, adolescents, or adults are generally safe.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Adverse effects, if any, are generally mild.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The rate of side effects depends on the vaccine in question.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some common side effects include fever, pain around the injection site, and muscle aches.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Additionally, some individuals may be allergic to ingredients in the vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The MMR vaccine is rarely associated with febrile seizures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Varicella vaccine is rarely associated with complications in immunodeficient individuals, and rotavirus vaccines are moderately associated with intussusception.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] At least 19 countries have no-fault compensation programs to provide compensation for those with severe adverse effects of vaccination.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The United States' program is known as the National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act, and the United Kingdom employs the Vaccine Damage Payment.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines typically contain attenuated, inactivated or dead organisms or purified products derived from them.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] There are several types of vaccines in use.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] These represent different strategies used to try to reduce the risk of illness while retaining the ability to induce a beneficial immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some vaccines contain live, attenuated microorganisms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Many of these are active viruses that have been cultivated under conditions that disable their virulent properties, or that use closely related but less dangerous organisms to produce a broad immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Although most attenuated vaccines are viral, some are bacterial in nature.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Examples include the viral diseases yellow fever, measles, mumps, and rubella, and the bacterial disease typhoid.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The live *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* vaccine developed by Calmette and Guérin is not made of a contagious strain but contains a virulently modified strain called "BCG" used to elicit an immune response to the vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The live attenuated vaccine containing strain *Yersinia pestis* EV is used for plague immunization.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Attenuated vaccines have some advantages and disadvantages.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Attenuated, or live, weakened, vaccines typically provoke more durable immunological responses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Attenuated vaccines also elicit a cellular and humoral response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] However, they may not be safe for use in immunocompromised individuals, and on rare occasions mutate to a virulent form and cause disease.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some vaccines contain microorganisms that have been killed or inactivated by physical or chemical means.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Examples include IPV (polio vaccine), hepatitis A vaccine, rabies vaccine and most influenza vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Toxoid vaccines are made from inactivated toxic compounds that cause illness rather than the microorganism.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Examples of toxoid-based vaccines include tetanus and diphtheria.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Not all toxoids are for microorganisms; for example, *Crotalus atrox* toxoid is used to vaccinate dogs against rattlesnake bites.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Rather than introducing an inactivated or attenuated microorganism to an immune system (which would constitute a "whole-agent" vaccine), a subunit vaccine uses a fragment of it to create an immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] One example is the subunit vaccine against hepatitis B, which is composed of only the surface proteins of the virus (previously extracted from the blood serum of chronically infected patients but now produced by recombination of the viral genes into yeast).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Other examples include the Gardasil virus-like particle human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine, the hemagglutinin and neuraminidase subunits of the influenza virus, and edible algae vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A subunit vaccine is being used for plague immunization.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Certain bacteria have a polysaccharide outer coat that is poorly immunogenic.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] By linking these outer coats to proteins (e.g., toxins), the immune system can be led to recognize the polysaccharide as if it were a protein antigen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This approach is used in the *Haemophilus influenzae* type B vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Outer membrane vesicles (OMVs) are naturally immunogenic and can be manipulated to produce potent vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The best known OMV vaccines are those developed for serotype B meningococcal disease.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Heterologous vaccines also known as "Jennerian vaccines", are vaccines that are pathogens of other animals that either do not cause disease or cause mild disease in the organism being treated.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The classic example is Jenner's use of cowpox to protect against smallpox.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A current example is the use of BCG vaccine made from *Mycobacterium bovis* to protect against tuberculosis.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Genetic vaccines are based on the principle of uptake of a nucleic acid into cells, whereupon a protein is produced according to the nucleic acid template.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This protein is usually the immunodominant antigen of the pathogen or a surface protein that enables the formation of neutralizing antibodies.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The subgroup of genetic vaccines encompass viral vector vaccines, RNA vaccines and DNA vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Viral vector vaccines use a safe virus to insert pathogen genes in the body to produce specific antigens, such as surface proteins, to stimulate an immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Viruses being researched for use as viral vectors include adenovirus, vaccinia virus, and VSV.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] An mRNA vaccine (or RNA vaccine) is a novel type of vaccine which is composed of the nucleic acid RNA, packaged within a vector such as lipid nanoparticles.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Among the COVID-19 vaccines are a number of RNA vaccines to combat the COVID-19 pandemic and some have been approved or have received emergency use authorization in some countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] For example, the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine and Moderna mRNA vaccine are approved for use in adults and children in the US.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A DNA vaccine uses a DNA plasmid (pDNA)) that encodes for an antigenic protein originating from the pathogen upon which the vaccine will be targeted. pDNA is inexpensive, stable, and relatively safe, making it an excellent option for vaccine delivery.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This approach offers a number of potential advantages over traditional approaches, including the stimulation of both B- and T-cell responses, improved vaccine stability, the absence of any infectious agent and the relative ease of large-scale manufacture.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Many innovative vaccines are also in development and use.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] While most vaccines are created using inactivated or attenuated compounds from microorganisms, synthetic vaccines are composed mainly or wholly of synthetic peptides, carbohydrates, or antigens.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines may be *monovalent* (also called *univalent*) or *multivalent* (also called *polyvalent*).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A monovalent vaccine is designed to immunize against a single antigen or single microorganism.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A multivalent or polyvalent vaccine is designed to immunize against two or more strains of the same microorganism, or against two or more microorganisms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The valency of a multivalent vaccine may be denoted with a Greek or Latin prefix (e.g., *bivalent*, *trivalent*, or *tetravalent/quadrivalent*).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In certain cases, a monovalent vaccine may be preferable for rapidly developing a strong immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] When two or more vaccines are mixed in the same formulation, the two vaccines can interfere.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This most frequently occurs with live attenuated vaccines, where one of the vaccine components is more robust than the others and suppresses the growth and immune response to the other components.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This phenomenon was noted in the trivalent Sabin polio vaccine, where the relative amount of serotype 2 virus in the vaccine had to be reduced to stop it from interfering with the "take" of the serotype 1 and 3 viruses in the vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] To accomplish this, the doses of serotypes 1 and 3 were increased in the vaccine in the early 1960s.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] It was also noted in a 2001 study to be a problem with dengue vaccines, where the DEN-3 serotype was found to predominate and suppress the response to DEN-1, -2 and -4 serotypes.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A vaccine dose contains many ingredients (such as stabilizers, adjuvants, residual inactivating ingredients, residual cell culture materials, residual antibiotics and preservatives) very little of which is the active ingredient, the immunogen.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A single dose may have merely nanograms of virus particles, or micrograms of bacterial polysaccharides.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A vaccine injection, oral drops or nasal spray is mostly water.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Other ingredients are added to boost the immune response, to ensure safety or help with storage, and a tiny amount of material is left-over from the manufacturing process.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Very rarely, these materials can cause an allergic reaction in people who are very sensitive to them.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines typically contain one or more adjuvants, used to boost the immune response.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Tetanus toxoid, for instance, is usually adsorbed onto alum.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This presents the antigen in such a way as to produce a greater action than the simple aqueous tetanus toxoid.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] People who have an adverse reaction to adsorbed tetanus toxoid may be given the simple vaccine when the time comes for a booster.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In the preparation for the 1990 Persian Gulf campaign, the whole cell pertussis vaccine was used as an adjuvant for anthrax vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This produces a more rapid immune response than giving only the anthrax vaccine, which is of some benefit if exposure might be imminent.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines may also contain preservatives to prevent contamination with bacteria or fungi.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Until recent years, the preservative thiomersal (a.k.a.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] *Thimerosal* in the US and Japan) was used in many vaccines that did not contain live viruses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] As of 2005, the only childhood vaccine in the U.S. that contains thiomersal in greater than trace amounts is the influenza vaccine, which is currently recommended only for children with certain risk factors.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Single-dose influenza vaccines supplied in the UK do not list thiomersal in the ingredients.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Preservatives may be used at various stages of the production of vaccines, and the most sophisticated methods of measurement might detect traces of them in the finished product, as they may in the environment and population as a whole.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Many vaccines need preservatives to prevent serious adverse effects such as *Staphylococcus* infection, which in one 1928 incident killed 12 of 21 children inoculated with a diphtheria vaccine that lacked a preservative.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Several preservatives are available, including thiomersal, phenoxyethanol, and formaldehyde.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Although controversial claims have been made that thiomersal contributes to autism, no convincing scientific evidence supports these claims.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Furthermore, a 10–11-year study of 657,461 children found that the MMR vaccine does not cause autism and actually reduced the risk of autism by seven percent.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Various fairly standardized abbreviations for vaccine names have developed, although the standardization is by no means centralized or global.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] For example, the vaccine names used in the United States have well-established abbreviations that are also widely known and used elsewhere.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] An extensive list of them provided in a sortable table and freely accessible is available at a US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention web page.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some examples are "DTaP" for diphtheria and tetanus toxoids and acellular pertussis vaccine, "DT" for diphtheria and tetanus toxoids, and "Td" for tetanus and diphtheria toxoids.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] At its page on tetanus vaccination, the CDC further explains that "Upper-case letters in these abbreviations denote full-strength doses of diphtheria (D) and tetanus (T) toxoids and pertussis (P) vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Lower-case "d" and "p" denote reduced doses of diphtheria and pertussis used in the adolescent/adult-formulations.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Another list of established vaccine abbreviations is at the CDC's page called "Vaccine Acronyms and Abbreviations", with abbreviations used on U.S. immunization records.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The United States Adopted Name system has some conventions for the word order of vaccine names, placing head nouns first and adjectives postpositively.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This is why the USAN for "OPV" is "poliovirus vaccine live oral" rather than "oral poliovirus vaccine".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Because preventive vaccines are predominantly evaluated in healthy population cohorts and distributed among the general population, a high standard of safety is required.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Upon developing countries adopting WHO guidelines for vaccine development and licensure, each country has its own responsibility to issue a national licensure, and to manage, deploy, and monitor the vaccine throughout its use in each nation.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Building trust and acceptance of a licensed vaccine among the public is a task of communication by governments and healthcare personnel to ensure a vaccination campaign proceeds smoothly, saves lives, and enables economic recovery.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] When a vaccine is licensed, it will initially be in limited supply due to variable manufacturing, distribution, and logistical factors, requiring an allocation plan for the limited supply and which population segments should be prioritized to first receive the vaccine.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines developed for multinational distribution via the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) require pre-qualification by the WHO to ensure international standards of quality, safety, immunogenicity, and efficacy for adoption by numerous countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The process requires manufacturing consistency at WHO-contracted laboratories following Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The WHO works with national agencies to monitor inspections of manufacturing facilities and distributors for compliance with GMP and regulatory oversight.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Some countries choose to buy vaccines licensed by reputable national organizations, such as EMA, FDA, or national agencies in other affluent countries, but such purchases typically are more expensive and may not have distribution resources suitable to local conditions in developing countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In the European Union (EU), vaccines for pandemic pathogens, such as seasonal influenza, are licensed EU-wide where all the member states comply ("centralized"), are licensed for only some member states ("decentralized"), or are licensed on an individual national level.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Generally, all EU states follow regulatory guidance and clinical programs defined by the European Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use (CHMP), a scientific panel of the European Medicines Agency (EMA) responsible for vaccine licensure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The CHMP is supported by several expert groups who assess and monitor the progress of a vaccine before and after licensure and distribution.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Under the FDA, the process of establishing evidence for vaccine clinical safety and efficacy is the same as for the approval process for prescription drugs.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Until a vaccine is in use amongst the general population, all potential adverse events from the vaccine may not be known, requiring manufacturers to conduct Phase IV studies for postmarketing surveillance of the vaccine while it is used widely in the public.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The WHO works with UN member states to implement post-licensing surveillance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The FDA relies on a Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System to monitor safety concerns about a vaccine throughout its use in the American public.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In order to provide the best protection, children are recommended to receive vaccinations as soon as their immune systems are sufficiently developed to respond to particular vaccines, with additional "booster" shots often required to achieve "full immunity".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This has led to the development of complex vaccination schedules.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The large number of vaccines and boosters recommended (up to 24 injections by age two) has led to problems with achieving full compliance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] To combat declining compliance rates, various notification systems have been instituted and many combination injections are now marketed (e.g., Pentavalent vaccine and MMRV vaccine), which protect against multiple diseases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Besides recommendations for infant vaccinations and boosters, many specific vaccines are recommended for other ages or for repeated injections throughout life – most commonly for measles, tetanus, influenza, and pneumonia.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Pregnant women are often screened for continued resistance to rubella.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The human papillomavirus vaccine is recommended in the U.S.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccine recommendations for the elderly concentrate on pneumonia and influenza, which are more deadly to that group.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In 2006, a vaccine was introduced against shingles, a disease caused by the chickenpox virus, which usually affects the elderly.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Scheduling and dosing of a vaccination may be tailored to the level of immunocompetence of an individual and to optimize population-wide deployment of a vaccine when its supply is limited, e.g. in the setting of a pandemic.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] One challenge in vaccine development is economic: Many of the diseases most demanding a vaccine, including HIV, malaria and tuberculosis, exist principally in poor countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In the United States, financial returns are usually minimal and the financial and other risks are great.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Most vaccine development to date has relied on "push" funding by government, universities and non-profit organizations.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Many vaccines have been highly cost effective and beneficial for public health.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The number of vaccines actually administered has risen dramatically in recent decades.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This increase, particularly in the number of different vaccines administered to children before entry into schools, may be due to government mandates and support, rather than economic incentive.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] According to the World Health Organization (WHO), the biggest barrier to vaccine production in less developed countries has not been patents, but the substantial financial, infrastructure, and workforce requirements needed for market entry.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines are complex mixtures of biological compounds, and unlike the case for prescription drugs, there are no true generic vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The vaccine produced by a new facility must undergo complete clinical testing for safety and efficacy by the manufacturer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] For most vaccines, specific processes in technology are patented.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] These can be circumvented by alternative manufacturing methods, but this required R&D infrastructure and a suitably skilled workforce.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In the case of a few relatively new vaccines, such as the human papillomavirus vaccine, the patents may impose an additional barrier.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccine production is fundamentally different from other kinds of manufacturing – including regular pharmaceutical manufacturing – in that vaccines are intended to be administered to millions of people of whom the vast majority are perfectly healthy.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This fact drives an extraordinarily rigorous production process with strict compliance requirements that go far beyond what is required of other products.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Depending upon the antigen, it can cost anywhere from US$50 to $500 million to build a vaccine production facility, which requires highly specialized equipment, clean rooms, and containment rooms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] There is a global scarcity of personnel with the right combination of skills, expertise, knowledge, competence and personality to staff vaccine production lines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] With the notable exceptions of Brazil, China, and India, many developing countries' educational systems are unable to provide enough qualified candidates, and vaccine makers based in such countries must hire expatriate personnel to keep production going.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Viruses are grown either on primary cells such as chicken eggs (e.g., for influenza) or on continuous cell lines such as cultured human cells (e.g., for hepatitis A).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Bacteria are grown in bioreactors (e.g., *Haemophilus influenzae* type b).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Likewise, a recombinant protein derived from the viruses or bacteria can be generated in yeast, bacteria, or cell cultures.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] After the antigen is generated, it is isolated from the cells used to generate it.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A virus may need to be inactivated, possibly with no further purification required.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Recombinant proteins need many operations involving ultrafiltration and column chromatography.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Finally, the vaccine is formulated by adding adjuvant, stabilizers, and preservatives as needed.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The adjuvant enhances the immune response to the antigen, stabilizers increase the storage life, and preservatives allow the use of multidose vials.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Combination vaccines are harder to develop and produce, because of potential incompatibilities and interactions among the antigens and other ingredients involved.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The final stage in vaccine manufacture before distribution is fill and finish, which is the process of filling vials with vaccines and packaging them for distribution.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Although this is a conceptually simple part of the vaccine manufacture process, it is often a bottleneck in the process of distributing and administering vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccine production techniques are evolving.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Cultured mammalian cells are expected to become increasingly important, compared to conventional options such as chicken eggs, due to greater productivity and low incidence of problems with contamination.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Recombination technology that produces genetically detoxified vaccines is expected to grow in popularity for the production of bacterial vaccines that use toxoids.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Combination vaccines are expected to reduce the quantities of antigens they contain, and thereby decrease undesirable interactions, by using pathogen-associated molecular patterns.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The companies with the highest market share in vaccine production are Merck, Sanofi, GlaxoSmithKline, Pfizer and Novartis, with 70% of vaccine sales concentrated in the EU or US (2013).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccine manufacturing plants require large capital investments ($50 million up to $300 million) and may take between 4 and 6 years to construct, with the full process of vaccine development taking between 10 and 15 years.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Manufacturing in developing countries is playing an increasing role in supplying these countries, specifically with regards to older vaccines and in Brazil, India and China.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] China's manufacturing capabilities are focused on supplying their own domestic need, with Sinopharm (CNPGC) alone providing over 85% of the doses for 14 different vaccines in China.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Brazil is approaching the point of supplying its own domestic needs using technology transferred from the developed world.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] One of the most common methods of delivering vaccines into the human body is injection.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The development of new delivery systems raises the hope of vaccines that are safer and more efficient to deliver and administer.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Lines of research include liposomes and *ISCOM* (immune stimulating complex).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Notable developments in vaccine delivery technologies have included oral vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Early attempts to apply oral vaccines showed varying degrees of promise, beginning early in the 20th century, at a time when the very possibility of an effective oral antibacterial vaccine was controversial.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] By the 1930s there was increasing interest in the prophylactic value of an oral typhoid fever vaccine for example.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] An oral polio vaccine turned out to be effective when vaccinations were administered by volunteer staff without formal training; the results also demonstrated increased ease and efficiency of administering the vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Effective oral vaccines have many advantages; for example, there is no risk of blood contamination.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccines intended for oral administration need not be liquid, and as solids, they commonly are more stable and less prone to damage or spoilage by freezing in transport and storage.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Such stability reduces the need for a "cold chain": the resources required to keep vaccines within a restricted temperature range from the manufacturing stage to the point of administration, which, in turn, may decrease costs of vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A microneedle approach, which is still in stages of development, uses "pointed projections fabricated into arrays that can create vaccine delivery pathways through the skin".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] An experimental needle-free vaccine delivery system is undergoing animal testing.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A stamp-size patch similar to an adhesive bandage contains about 20,000 microscopic projections per square cm.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This dermal administration potentially increases the effectiveness of vaccination, while requiring less vaccine than injection.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Vaccinations of animals are used both to prevent their contracting diseases and to prevent transmission of disease to humans.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Both animals kept as pets and animals raised as livestock are routinely vaccinated.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In some instances, wild populations may be vaccinated.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] This is sometimes accomplished with vaccine-laced food spread in a disease-prone area and has been used to attempt to control rabies in raccoons.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Where rabies occurs, rabies vaccination of dogs may be required by law.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Other canine vaccines include canine distemper, canine parvovirus, infectious canine hepatitis, adenovirus-2, leptospirosis, *Bordetella*, canine parainfluenza virus, and Lyme disease, among others.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Cases of veterinary vaccines used in humans have been documented, whether intentional or accidental, with some cases of resultant illness, most notably with brucellosis.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] However, the reporting of such cases is rare and very little has been studied about the safety and results of such practices.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] With the advent of aerosol vaccination in veterinary clinics, human exposure to pathogens not naturally carried in humans, such as *Bordetella bronchiseptica*, has likely increased in recent years.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In some cases, most notably rabies, the parallel veterinary vaccine against a pathogen may be as much as orders of magnitude more economical than the human one.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] A common issue with animal vaccination is that it interferes with immunological tests as both infection and vaccination can result in antibodies against an antigen being made.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] To solve this issue, special *marker vaccines* are created using pathogen strains carrying at least one epitope less than the equivalent wild microorganism.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] An accompanying diagnostic test that detects the antibody against that epitope assists in identifying whether the animal has been vaccinated or not.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The first marker vaccines and companion diagnostic tests were developed by J.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] T. van Oirschot and colleagues at the Central Veterinary Institute in Lelystad, The Netherlands.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] They found that some existing vaccines against pseudorabies (also termed Aujeszky's disease) had deletions in their viral genome (among which was the gE gene).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Monoclonal antibodies were produced against that deletion and selected to develop an ELISA that demonstrated antibodies against gE.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] In addition, novel genetically engineered gE-negative vaccines were constructed.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Along the same lines, DIVA vaccines and companion diagnostic tests against bovine herpesvirus 1 infections have been developed.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] The DIVA strategy has been applied in various countries to successfully eradicate pseudorabies virus from those countries.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Swine populations were intensively vaccinated and monitored by the companion diagnostic test and, subsequently, the infected pigs were removed from the population.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p01] Bovine herpesvirus 1 DIVA vaccines are also widely used in practice.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Prior to the introduction of vaccination with material from cases of cowpox (heterotypic immunisation), smallpox could be prevented by deliberate variolation with smallpox virus.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] According to historian Joseph Needham, Taoists in China as far back as the 10th century practiced a form of inoculation and passed it down through oral tradition, though Needham's claim has been criticized since the practice was not written about.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] The Chinese also practiced the oldest documented use of variolation, dating back to the fifteenth century.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] They implemented a method of "nasal insufflation" administered by blowing powdered smallpox material, usually scabs, up the nostrils.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Various insufflation techniques have been recorded throughout the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries within China.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Two reports on the Chinese practice of inoculation were received by the Royal Society in London in 1700; one by Martin Lister who received a report by an employee of the East India Company stationed in China and another by Clopton Havers.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In France, Voltaire reports that the Chinese have practiced variolation "these hundred years".
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Mary Wortley Montagu, who had witnessed variolation in Turkey, had her four-year-old daughter variolated in the presence of physicians of the Royal Court in 1721 upon her return to England.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Later on that year, Charles Maitland conducted an experimental variolation of six prisoners in Newgate Prison in London.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] The experiment was a success, and soon variolation was drawing attention from the royal family, who helped promote the procedure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] However, in 1783, several days after Prince Octavius of Great Britain was inoculated, he died.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 1796, the physician Edward Jenner took pus from the hand of a milkmaid with cowpox, scratched it into the arm of an 8-year-old boy, James Phipps, and six weeks later variolated the boy with smallpox, afterwards observing that he did not catch smallpox.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Jenner extended his studies and, in 1798, reported that his vaccine was safe in children and adults, and could be transferred from arm-to-arm, which reduced reliance on uncertain supplies from infected cows.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 1804, the Spanish Balmis smallpox vaccination expedition to Spain's colonies Mexico and Philippines used the arm-to-arm transport method to get around the fact the vaccine survived for only 12 days *in vitro*.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Since vaccination with cowpox was much safer than smallpox inoculation, the latter, though still widely practiced in England, was banned in 1840.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Following on from Jenner's work, the second generation of vaccines was introduced in the 1880s by Louis Pasteur who developed vaccines for chicken cholera and anthrax, and from the late nineteenth century vaccines were considered a matter of national prestige.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] National vaccination policies were adopted and compulsory vaccination laws were passed.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 1931 Alice Miles Woodruff and Ernest Goodpasture documented that the fowlpox virus could be grown in embryonated chicken egg.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Soon scientists began cultivating other viruses in eggs.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Eggs were used for virus propagation in the development of a yellow fever vaccine in 1935 and an influenza vaccine in 1945.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 1959 growth media and cell culture replaced eggs as the standard method of virus propagation for vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Vaccinology flourished in the twentieth century, which saw the introduction of several successful vaccines, including those against diphtheria, measles, mumps, and rubella.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Major achievements included the development of the polio vaccine in the 1950s and the eradication of smallpox during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Maurice Hilleman was the most prolific of the developers of the vaccines in the twentieth century.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] As vaccines became more common, many people began taking them for granted.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] However, vaccines remain elusive for many important diseases, including herpes simplex, malaria, gonorrhea, and HIV.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] First generation vaccines are whole-organism vaccines – either live and weakened, or killed forms.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Live, attenuated vaccines, such as smallpox and polio vaccines, are able to induce killer T-cell (TC or CTL) responses, helper T-cell (TH) responses and antibody immunity.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] However, attenuated forms of a pathogen can convert to a dangerous form and may cause disease in immunocompromised vaccine recipients (such as those with AIDS).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] While killed vaccines do not have this risk, they cannot generate specific killer T-cell responses and may not work at all for some diseases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Second generation vaccines were developed to reduce the risks from live vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] These are subunit vaccines, consisting of specific protein antigens (such as tetanus or diphtheria toxoid) or recombinant protein components (such as the hepatitis B surface antigen).
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] They can generate TH and antibody responses, but not killer T cell responses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] RNA vaccines and DNA vaccines are examples of third generation vaccines.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 2016 a DNA vaccine for the Zika virus began testing at the National Institutes of Health.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Separately, Inovio Pharmaceuticals and GeneOne Life Science began tests of a different DNA vaccine against Zika in Miami.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Manufacturing the vaccines in volume was unsolved as of 2016.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Clinical trials for DNA vaccines to prevent HIV are underway. mRNA vaccines such as BNT162b2 were developed in the year 2020 with the help of Operation Warp Speed and massively deployed to combat the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 2021, Katalin Karikó and Drew Weissman received Columbia University's Horwitz Prize for their pioneering research in mRNA vaccine technology.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Since at least 2013, scientists have been trying to develop synthetic third-generation vaccines by reconstructing the outside structure of a virus; it was hoped that this will help prevent vaccine resistance.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Principles that govern the immune response can now be used in tailor-made vaccines against many noninfectious human diseases, such as cancers and autoimmune disorders.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] For example, the experimental vaccine CYT006-AngQb has been investigated as a possible treatment for high blood pressure.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Factors that affect the trends of vaccine development include progress in translatory medicine, demographics, regulatory science, political, cultural, and social responses.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] The idea of vaccine production via transgenic plants was identified as early as 2003.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Plants such as tobacco, potato, tomato, and banana can have genes inserted that cause them to produce vaccines usable for humans.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] In 2005, bananas were developed that produce a human vaccine against hepatitis B.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Vaccine hesitancy is a delay in acceptance, or refusal of vaccines despite the availability of vaccine services.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] The term covers outright refusals to vaccinate, delaying vaccines, accepting vaccines but remaining uncertain about their use, or using certain vaccines but not others.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] There is an overwhelming scientific consensus that vaccines are generally safe and effective.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] Vaccine hesitancy often results in disease outbreaks and deaths from vaccine-preventable diseases.
[src:cold-chain-monitoring/vaccine-p02] The World Health Organization therefore characterized vaccine hesitancy as one of the top ten global health threats in 2019.
